Comment: [%clk 0:05:03] Not the most common answer, but one of the best.
[%clk 0:05:09] Icelandic, my favourite.
[%clk 0:05:13] The point is black has two developed pieces and white none. It is actually not such a great advantage, though, and has to be handled carefully. I didn't.

[%clk 0:05:14] Not forced still to employ the dsb on e7. I like it on d6. Now white can go d5, and if Bxd5, QxB, NxQ, BxQ, and black has Nb4 as a threat, forcing Bd6, NxB, cxN, after which black has still RxBd8 and is in good shape.
[%clk 0:05:07] Where I want it. Of course white can reject it with c4-c5. Two tempos, and I can still go c6 and Bb4+.
[%clk 0:04:47] I would say this is too passive.

[%clk 0:05:09] I plan all the way to castle queenside, so I'm not scared in opening the kingside. By playing this, I accept Bh4, g5 and the risky piece per two pawns sac. A fun game, the result difficult to predict. I also accept Bg3, and I will answer Qe7 and leave the exchange to him.
[%clk 0:04:45] Does this look like a bad move?
[%clk 0:05:12] Sticking to my plan.
[%clk 0:04:48] Thank you white. Can you see you are inviting me?
[%clk 0:04:49] c4 was strongly needed, in order to force the deployment of my dsb (I'll go to f4 in case of c5). This is a mistake, even fearing Ng4, because it opens the way to my g pawn.
[%clk 0:05:14] Maybe too slow, but hey, I'm losing too many games no to be a little wiser.
